fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2mitche:   

First, I am referring to simple NMF, and not 2-way NMF or XYZ -- variants of NMF.
Here is the basic idea of NMF:
Opener bids 1 of a minor (or rarely, 1@h), and responder bids 1 of a Major.  
Opener rebids 1NT and now responder, who bid 1@S (let us say) with a 5-card suit would like to play in a 
5-3 fit if there is one, or in NT if there isn’t.
So let's say for discussion that the auction began 
1@C - 1@S
1NT - ?
- A 2@s rebid by responder is a ^*bsign-off^*n, showing 6 spades and a weak hand, something like 
@sQ10xxxx, @hxx, @dKxx, @cJx.|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|
- A 3@s bid is ^*binvitational^*n, showing around 11 points and 6 spades, e.g. @sKQ10xxx, @hxx, @dKJx, @cQx.
So we take care of all cases where responder has 6 spades with a spade rebid:  
2@S is sign off, 3@S is invitational and 4@s is minimum opener, wanting to play in spades.
Note that 1NT by opener almost always shows at least 2 cards support. |
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|

Now, what does responder do with 5 spades?
- With a hand of less than invitational strength, he just passes 1NT.|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|
- With invitational strength or greater, he bids 2@D  -- the "new" (i.e. unbid) minor.
This is artificial and must be alerted.  It asks opener to describe his hand further.
Opener's rebids: In our sample auction, 2@h shows 4 hearts. 2@s shows 3 spades and ^*udenies^*n 4 hearts.
2NT denies either.

NOTE that since opener limited his hand (1NT), there is no need for him to jump or do anything other than 
make a minimum rebid, 2@h, 2@s or 2NT.
One of my friends calls New Minor Forcing the "5 and 10 bid" - 5 spades/hearts, 10 points.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
Opener, with both   4@H's   ^*band^*n   3@s'S - bids the 4-card @H-suit first. 
You will prefer a 4-4 fit to a 5-3 fit when both are available.
When responder fails to raise 2@h by bidding 2NT, opener will, with a 3 card-@S support as well, 
bid either 3 or 4 spades.
Here is one instance where I think fast arrival is wrong. 
If opener has a minimum, and responder bids 2NT, also showing a minimum, 
then it is foolish to push to 4@S just because  responder has 10 points. 

Suppose opener's rebid is 2NT.  Opener does not have 3 spades nor 4 hearts.
Responder rebids now: 
- 3@h  if he is 5-5 in the Majors.      Otherwise he bids 3NT   (or with a bad 10, passes).
Remember that opener has just 14 HCP maximum, so responder will bid game with a good 11 or more, 
and flip a coin with 10 points.

OK, one variation. Suppose it goes: 
1@C  - 1@H 
1NT - 2@d
2@s !

Now opener does not have 4 spades, right?    
With 4 spades, opener would rebid 1@S not 1NT.    (MM: Unless otherwise agreed)
So when responder wheels out the NMF bid, opener's 2@s is an "impossible" bid (at most a 3-card suit) -- right?
So some pairs use this "impossible" bid to show a ^*bmaximum and a good heart fit^*n, as compared with 2@h.
I recommend that you use that variant ONLY in established partnerships where you have discussed things thoroughly.
The NMF bid is alertable, - opener's rebids are not alertable unless you use 2@s for something else.

OK Let's play!

