at|mitche: Bidding:  I think that pretty much everyone plays a 2@s bid over the 1@D opener as a preemptive bid,
showing 6 spades and nothing else, - in other words, South's hand, but minus the @DK.
When you bid 2@s you deny any outside Ace or King, 
so partner is in a position to know whether or not to take a save.
Here, assuming that 2@S was preemptive, North has a pretty clear cut raise to 3. 
Turns out that bidding 3@s is the winning bid, because E/W are going to make 4@h.  
Even if declarer misguesses hearts, E/W make 3.



